automata

Class Cell

  • java.lang.Object
    • systems.AbstractAgent
      • automata.Cell
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    ConwayCell, ImmigrationCell, SchellingCell

    public abstract class Cell
extends AbstractAgent
    Represents a cell evolving in a grid. This model may have multiple states according to its neighbourhood.
    See Also:
    Grid

    • Field Detail

      • grid

        protected Grid grid
        The grid in which the cell evolves.

      • i

        protected int i
        The x-position (height) of the cell.

      • j

        protected int j
        The y-position (width) of the cell.

      • states

        protected java.util.List<State> states
        The list of possible states for the cell. With this reference, we can build a transition function.

      • state

        protected State state
        The current state of the cell.

      • firstState

        protected State firstState
        (Back-up). The first state of the cell.

      • saveState

        protected State saveState
        The next state of the cell. This attribute is used because all the cells have to check their next state (via neighbours) before one can be changed.

      • neighbours

        protected java.util.List<Cell> neighbours
        The eight neighbours of the cell. To avoid searching neighbours of the cell at each generation, this attribute stores them.

    • Method Detail

      • emerge

        public final void emerge()
        Gives birth to the cell. Updates its first state and saves it.
        See Also:
        initState()

      • restart

        public final void restart()
        Restarts the cell. As the only thing that evolves in the cell is its status, this method only set the current state to the firstState.

      • saveNextState

        public final void saveNextState()
        Saves the next state of the cell. First, all cells check their next state and save it. Then, all cells adopt their new states.
        See Also:
        saveState

      • changeState

        public void changeState()
        Changes the state of the cell, according to "saveState". Once all cells know their future state, they can update.
        See Also:
        saveState

      • findNeighbours

        public void findNeighbours()
        Finds the eight neighbours of the cell. As long as the grid is circular, a cell will always have eight neighbours.

      • countNeighbours

        public int countNeighbours(State state)
        Counts the number of neighbouring cells in the state "state". If the state is null, throws an IllegalArgumentException.
        Parameters:
        state - The state that the neighbourhood should have.
        Returns:
        The number of neighbours in the state "state"

      • getState

        public State getState()
        State getter.
        Returns:
        The current state of the cell.

        public void setState(State state)
        State setter.
        Parameters:
        state - The state to assign to the cell.

      • setSaveState

        public void setSaveState(State saveState)
        Save state setter.
        Parameters:
        saveState - The save state to assign to the cell.

      • initState

        protected abstract State initState()
        Assigns the state of the cell at its creation. Cells can't be "stateless" objects. Each cell should have a first state when being instanciated. This init state may be either always the same one, or decided with randomness.
        Returns:
        The first state of the cell at the beginning.

      • nextState

        protected abstract State nextState()
        Assigns the next state of the cell. Cells evolve due to their neighbours. Each cell should always have a state. This method is not intended to assign the future state. It's the "transition function" of the automaton.
        Returns:
        The next state of the cell depending on its current state.
